            "content": "# TODO - min-dl improvements\n\nInspired by analysis of externals/lecopzer and externals/mgood7123 forks,\nplus review feedback from Gemini and Codex.\n\n## Bug fixes (critical)\n\n- [ ] loader.c:321 RELA addend not used. `*addr += load_bias` is correct for REL\n      (ARM) but RELA (x86-64, aarch64) requires `*addr = load_bias + reloc->r_addend`.\n      Currently works because static linkers write the addend into memory, but the\n      ELF spec does not guarantee this. Real-world RELA relocations will break.\n- [ ] loader.c:298 uses `ro_load->p_offset + load_bias` for ro_start, but p_offset\n      is the file offset, not virtual address. Should use `ro_load->p_vaddr + load_bias`\n      for correct read-only section bounds checking during relocation. The current code\n      works by accident when file offset == vaddr (common but not guaranteed by ELF spec).\n- [ ] loader.c:298 ro_load dereferenced unconditionally. An ET_DYN with only writable\n      PT_LOAD segments (no read-only segment) leaves ro_load as NULL, crashing here.\n      Guard with NULL check and skip RO-range handling, or derive protections from the\n      segment that owns each relocation target.\n- [ ] loader.c:239 mmap() return value unchecked. MAP_FAILED (-1) produces a bogus\n      load_bias, leading to wild pointers and silent corruption in all subsequent\n      relocation and segment mapping. Same for mprotect() calls at lines 275, 319, 322.\n      Check every syscall result and abort cleanly.\n\n## Bug fixes (high)\n\n- [ ] loader.c:183 no error check on open() return value. A failed open returns -1,\n      then pread() on fd=-1 silently produces garbage instead of a clear error.\n- [ ] loader.c:185,213 pread() return values unchecked. Partial reads leave ehdr/phdr\n      partially or wholly uninitialized, then the loader branches on indeterminate data.\n      Require each pread() to return the full requested byte count.\n- [ ] loader.c:151 get_dynamic_entry() returns ElfW(Word), which is 32-bit. On x86-64\n      and aarch64, dynamic entry values (DT_SYMTAB, DT_RELA, DT_RELASZ, DT_PLTGOT,\n      DT_JMPREL) are 64-bit addresses/sizes. The 32-bit return truncates them silently.\n      Should return ElfW(Xword) or use d_un.d_ptr for address-valued tags.\n- [ ] loader.c:318-319 mprotect grants PROT_WRITE alone (no PROT_READ), which faults\n      on architectures where read permission is required to write. The relocation\n      `*addr += load_bias` is a read-modify-write. Should be PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE,\n      or better: `prot_from_phdr(ro_load) | PROT_WRITE`.\n- [ ] loader.c:182 hardcodes pagesize to 0x1000. Should use sysconf(_SC_PAGESIZE) or\n      getauxval(AT_PAGESZ) to support 16K/64K page systems (e.g., Apple Silicon, some\n      aarch64 Linux kernels). mmap/mprotect will fail with EINVAL on non-4K systems.\n\n## Bug fixes (medium)\n\n- [ ] loader.c:195 architecture validation too loose. Accepts EM_X86_64, EM_ARM, and\n      EM_AARCH64 regardless of build target. A native x86-64 build loading an ARM .so\n      will pass the check, then crash on the host-specific trampoline. Should also verify\n      EI_CLASS (32 vs 64-bit) and EI_DATA (endianness) match the compiled binary.\n- [ ] loader.c:367 api_set_plt_entry() writes pltgot[import_id] with no bounds check.\n      A bad import_id from a resolver becomes an out-of-bounds write into the loaded\n      image. Record PLT entry count from dynamic tags and validate.\n- [ ] loader.c:233 integer overflow in span calculation. Crafted p_vaddr + p_memsz\n      values can wrap, producing an undersized mmap and later out-of-bounds access.\n      Same risk in round_up() and the various last_end/file_end arithmetic. Validate\n      before mapping.\n- [ ] loader.c:175 system_plt_resolver called before api_set_plt_resolver() leaves\n      user_plt_resolver as NULL. If an import is called before resolver setup, the\n      trampoline jumps through NULL. Reject or trap explicitly.\n\n## Bug fixes (minor)\n\n- [ ] loader.c:313 typo in comment: \"loactes\" should be \"locates\".\n- [ ] Makefile:50 uses recursive make (`@make CROSS_COMPILE=...`) instead of\n      $(MAKE), which breaks with -j parallel builds and ignores parent make flags.\n- [ ] loader.c:16 MAX_PHNUM is 12. Modern GCC/Clang can generate more than 12\n      program headers (PT_GNU_STACK, PT_GNU_RELRO, PT_GNU_EH_FRAME, PT_NOTE, etc.).\n      Should be at least 32, or dynamically sized from ehdr.e_phnum.\n\n## Design issues\n\n- [ ] loader.c:82 fail() calls exit(), which terminates the host process. A loader\n      library should not kill its caller. Return NULL with an error code, or provide\n      a user-configurable error handler. The writev-to-stderr + exit(2) pattern is\n      acceptable for standalone tools but not for a reusable library API.\n\n## Symbol resolution (inspired by mgood7123)\n\nmgood7123 built a full dlopen/dlsym-style loader with symbol table parsing.\nThe current min-dl only resolves PLT imports via a user-supplied callback (import_id).\nExtending to name-based resolution would make this a more complete dynamic linker.\n\n- [ ] Parse .dynsym and .dynstr from PT_DYNAMIC to support symbol lookup by name.\n      get_dynamic_entry() already walks DT entries -- add DT_SYMTAB, DT_STRTAB,\n      DT_HASH/DT_GNU_HASH extraction.\n- [ ] Implement api_lookup_symbol(dloader_p, const char *name) -> void* to provide\n      dlsym-equivalent functionality. Add to DLoader API struct.\n- [ ] Handle additional relocation types beyond R_*_RELATIVE: at minimum\n      R_X86_64_GLOB_DAT, R_X86_64_JUMP_SLOT, R_ARM_GLOB_DAT, R_ARM_JUMP_SLOT,\n      R_AARCH64_GLOB_DAT, R_AARCH64_JUMP_SLOT for loading real shared libraries.\n- [ ] Support DT_INIT/DT_FINI and DT_INIT_ARRAY/DT_FINI_ARRAY for constructor and\n      destructor execution. mgood7123's DT_INIT.c demonstrates the need.\n\n## Robustness\n\n- [ ] Add api_unload(dloader_p) to munmap loaded segments and free the handle.\n      Currently there is no way to unload a library (resource leak).\n- [ ] Handle the case where DT_PLTGOT exists but DT_JMPREL does not (or vice versa).\n      Latent issue -- these fields are not consumed in a way that crashes today, but\n      will become active once PLT resolution is extended.\n\n## Testing\n\n- [ ] Add cross-compilation and qemu-based test targets for ARM and AARCH64 to CI\n      (currently only documented in Makefile, no automated test pipeline).\n- [ ] Add a test for loading a library with no PLT imports (pure export-only .so)\n      to exercise the relocation path without PLT resolver setup.\n- [ ] Add a test that verifies the read-only section protection is actually restored\n      after relocation (mprotect back to original permissions).\n- [ ] Test with position-dependent relocations and verify proper error handling for\n      unsupported relocation types (currently assert(0) -- should fail gracefully).\n\n## Build system\n\n- [ ] Support RISC-V (riscv64) architecture: add arch/riscv64.h with assembly macros,\n      relocation case R_RISCV_RELATIVE in loader.c, and EM_RISCV in machine check.\n- [ ] Add `make check_all` target that runs native + all cross-architecture tests in\n      one command.\n- [ ] Add CFLAGS knob for building with sanitizers (-fsanitize=address,undefined) to\n      catch memory bugs in the loader itself.\n",
